status_message:
I am watching the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence hearing with NSA Director Admiral Rogers and FBI Director Comey on Russian intervention in our election. Now, let me begin by stating that I do believe it rather perplexing, and irresponsible, for President Trump to make an assertion about something for which he had no evidence -- Obama ordering wiretapping of Trump Tower. However, where was the Democrat indignation over Barack Obama's statement of having more flexibility after his reelection to Russian President Dmitry Medvedev? Where was the liberal progressive reaction when Hillary Clinton was involved with uranium sales to Russia? Why was there no grandstanding by the left when it was Barack Obama interfering with the Israeli elections? And let's be honest, there have been statements from former CIA Director Morrell and head of the DNI General Clapper who've said there's no there, there, with any evidence of Trump campaign collusion with Russia.

What upsets me most about all of this, is the lack of adult leadership. We have just too much foolish subjective assumptions that are less than speculative. It's all a bunch of political distractions. Conclusion, President Trump should never have posted that tweet and the Democrats need to stop the Russia witch hunt; they have enough dirt themselves.

status_message:
Enjoy this short 4:30 video courtesy of Dan Thomas. This is one of my favorite songs by the Christian rock group, Newsboys.

Sometimes we need to be reminded of the splendor of God's work and His omnipotence. Just as when man thought he could build a tower and touch God, we need to be reminded that all is in His able and capable hands. Such a wonder, and it is not man made, because what we make fades away into oblivion, as Percy Shelly's poem of Ozymandius reminds us all;

I met a traveller from an antique land
Who said: "Two vast and trunkless legs of stone
Stand in the desert . . . Near them, on the sand,
Half sunk, a shattered visage lies, whose frown,
And wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,
Tell that its sculptor well those passions read
Which yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,
The hand that mocked them, and the heart that fed:
And on the pedestal these words appear:
'My name is Ozymandias, king of kings:
Look on my works, ye Mighty, and despair!'
Nothing beside remains. Round the decay
Of that colossal wreck, boundless and bare
The lone and level sands stretch far away."
There is one King of Kings who is everlasting and all creation sings in wonder, let every rock cry out, let every knee bow down…you open up my eyes to Wonder. What a powerful message, and reminder to us of our finite state, and His infiniteness.

status_message: I am a true son of Atlanta, born and raised. And I'm a proud Atlantan who today watched my hometown Atlanta Falcons defeat the Green Bay Packers in the NFC Championship game. What a way to say goodbye to the Georgia Dome with a 44-21 win over the venerable Packers…sadly, I never saw a game in the Georgia Dome in its 25 years of existence. However, I will get back to the new Mercedes Benz Stadium. But congratulations to the Atlanta Falcons owner, Arthur Blank, and Coach Dan Quinn for a great season and off to the Super Bowl against the New England Patriots in Super Bowl LI in Houston, Texas. status_message:
Happy Thanksgiving everyone!  It's a very special day in the West family as we are together giving thanks. But today means we no longer have any teenagers in our home. Our youngest daughter Austen turns 20 today and it seems like just yesterday we were bringing Austen Brianna Graham-West home from Stormont-Vail hospital in Topeka Kansas to 300 Morning Glory in Manhattan Kansas, our first house. And now, that little bundle of joy is about to join an incredible legacy. She will be the fifth generation in our family to serve this nation in uniform…Austen has decided to contract as an Army ROTC Cadet. Austen will be the first female in the West line of Guardians of the Republic, and the third officer. If she toughs it out, Angela and I get to place those Second Lieutenant insignia boards on her shoulders. What an immense honor that will be, just as it was presiding over my nephew's promotion ceremony to Major at Ft. Leavenworth watching his dad, my older brother, a Vietnam Marine, place his gold oak leaf insignia boards on his shoulders. That is why America is an exceptional country - generations stepping up to answer the call to arms!

Happy Birthday Beetlejuice!  Mom and Dad are proud of ya!

status_message:
Today is November 10th, the day that 241 years ago one of the greatest fighting forces the world has ever known was created at a place called Tun Tavern. They have been called Leathernecks, earned during the expedition against the Barbary Pirates ending in Tripoli, under the leadership of First Lieutenant Presley O'Bannon. In World War I, the Germans called them Devil Dogs, earned during their tenacious offensive actions in Belleau Wood in France. They sloughed it out island by island in the Pacific during World War II and gave this Nation one of the most iconic pictures in our military history, raising the American flag on Mount Suribachi, the black volcanic sands of Iwo Jima. At a faraway place called Chosin Reservoir during the Korean War, 10 Chinese divisions surrounded Col. Lewis Berwell Puller's 1st Marines. The indomitable "Chesty" Puller saw the situation with his own brand of logic: "Those poor bastards," he said. "They've got us right where we want them. We can fire in any direction now!"

They fight in the jungles, they fight in the desert sands…they attack from air, on land, or sea. They are the few, they are the Proud. My older Brother once wore the Scarlet and Gold and fought as a combat infantryman. They are the ones who keep their sacred honor clean. Happy 241st Birthday to my Brothers and Sister Warriors, the United States Marines.

Semper Fidelis, Ooh Rah!!!!

status_message: 229 years ago on September 17, 1787t our Constitution was signed in Philadelphia. Our great rule of law was set in motion, yet today, we hardly teach it, and most Americans have no clue about its content -- especially our president. The story we should all recall is that of Benjamin Franklin being asked by the Philadelphia socialite, Mrs. Powell, "Well Doctor, what is it that we have, a Republic, or a monarchy?" Franklin replied, "a Republic if you can keep it." That was the challenge issued those 229 years ago. So today ask yourself, what are you doing to keep this Republic? It's a simple question, and sadly, there are those seeking to fundamentally transform the United States of America -- into what?

status_message: Today is the 15th remembrance of the horrific Islamic terrorist attack of 9-11. Just as my Dad had Pearl Harbor, this was the clarion call for my generation; we both answered the call to arms for our America. And being a Tennessee Volunteer, last night watching our National Anthem being sung and the display across Bristol Motor Speedway warmed my soul. This is a day that shall live in infamy when our way of life was attacked, and I will never forget being at Camp Lejeune and watching the second plane strike the World Trade Tower. Today we remember what unites us and against whom we must never relent, until they are defeated. Now, if some spoiled overpaid football player believes this is a day for foolish, they will receive the brunt of a Patriot's version of freedom of expression. Never forget this day…never forget who the enemy is, for it certainly is not these United States of America, and that for which it stands.

Last evening I was honored to be the keynote speaker for the Torch of Freedom Foundation's Patriot Academy in Austin, Texas. The Patriot Academy brings together some 150 students, aged 16-25, in a week of mock legislative procedure to equip a new generation of leaders to champion the cause of freedom and truth in government, media, entertainment, and education. The Foundation seeks to bring the nation back to the principles upon which we were founded.

I am reminded of President Ronald Reagan's words, "Freedom is never more than one generation from extinction." If there is one thing we all witnessed over the past four days emanating from Philadelphia, ironically so, is that which began 240 years ago, the birth of a Constitutional Republic, is endangered for our future generations. Tonight, I along with several other Veterans, passed the "Torch of Freedom" to these 150. God bless America, God bless the Torch of Freedom Foundation.

What the Islamic jihadists are doing can't be separated from the theocratic-political totalitarian ideology we know as Islam. It's a phase that must be understood, or else we shall not be successful in this current conflagration, which is nothing more than another chapter in the ongoing battle between Dar-al-Islam and Dar-al Harb. The book describes each of the 44 militant Islamic jihadist groups, from Boko Haram in Nigeria to Abu Sayyaf in the Philippines, that comprise the global Islamic jihad. I  wholeheartedly recommend this book -- it concisely aggregates that which many of us have already studied and understand.

This is a global movement that we must acknowledge and engage, and stop playing whack-a-mole.

status_message:
Happy Texas Independence Day y'all! 180 years ago today, folks here stood up for liberty and freedom and declared independence for Texas from Mexico.  I'm in my second year being a Texas resident but being a Tennessee Volunteer, it's my pleasure and honor to have joined the legacy of men who came here to stand with the Texans.  And being a former Member of Congress, there's much I share with the favored son of Tennessee, Davy Crockett. It was Crockett who famously said after losing his Congressional reelection, "You all may go to hell, I'm going to Texas."

But what I find even more historic and interesting is the link between one of my favorite stories from military history and Texas independence. It was back in 490 BC when tyranny stood before liberty at a place called Thermopylae and Xerxes and the invading Persians demanded King Leonidas and the Spartans to lay down their arms. Leonidas replied with the words, "Molon Labe." On November 25, 1778 , 127 Continental Soldiers and some militiamen totaling about 200, under the command of Colonel John McIntosh, stood defiantly before a British force in my home state of Georgia at Ft. Morris and responded to the request of surrender to the British commander Colonel Fuser with "come and take it." On October 2, 1835 Mexico's military commander of Texas, Colonel Domingo de Ugartechea, dispatched a company of Dragoons to retrieve the cannon from the Texians at the town of Gonzales. Upon demanding surrender of the cannon, the Texians responded, "come and take it" – they voted to fight and deployed 140 to drive off the Mexicans. The words of Leonidas translate to "Come, Take." Those words are part of the American fabric and our desire to be free and independent when we are faced by tyranny. Happy Independence Day to the place I now call home, the great state and former Republic of Texas. God bless Texas y'all!"

I wholeheartedly recommend this book, because if we're to live up to Benjamin Franklin's challenge to keep this Republic, we cannot allow certain forces to constrain our freedom of speech. Who would have ever thought our college campuses would become havens of "safe spaces" that deter free and open debate? We live in a society now where a certain group of individuals are determining what is "proper" to be said…while those proselytizing the undermining of our constitutional Republic are protected. We're on a battlefield of ideals and if we succumb to political correctness, only one side gets to be heard in this seminal confrontation between constitutional conservatism, liberty, and progressive socialism, tyranny. Nick's book is a must-read.

status_message: I was born in 1961. That year, there was a "wade-in" non-violent protest at Ft. Lauderdale beach because blacks weren't allowed to swim there. Fifty years later, in January of 2011, I was sworn in as the congressional representative of Florida's 22 District, encompassing that very same beach all the way to Palm Beach.  As we remember Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. this day, this son of Atlanta's Old Fourth Ward, educated in the shadow of Ebenezer Baptist Church just wants to say thanks. Thank you Dr. King for setting a goal and a dream enabling me to enjoy the blessed liberties, freedoms, and opportunities of being a citizen of the greatest nation the world has known, America. And tonight I'll be at Grand Valley State University in MI to discuss American exceptionalism and Dr. King's dream. I saw the weather forecast; boy is it cold up there!

status_message:
As I was doing some reading this Sunday afternoon and reflecting on these past seven years of Obama's reign, I was reminded of this seminal quote attributed to the great Roman statesman and philosopher Marcus Tulius Cicero: "A nation can survive its fools, and even the ambitious. But it cannot survive treason from within. An enemy at the gates is less formidable, for he is known and carries his banner openly. But the traitor moves amongst those within the gate freely, his sly whispers rustling through all the alleys, heard in the very halls of government itself. For the traitor appears not a traitor; he speaks in accents familiar to his victims, and he wears their face and their arguments, he appeals to the baseness that lies deep in the hearts of all men. He rots the soul of a nation, he works secretly and unknown in the night to undermine the pillars of the city, he infects the body politic so that it can no longer resist. A murderer is less to fear."

Sadly, there is much evidence in President Obama's policies from 2009 to present that supports this quote from Cicero. This is what I will see and be reminded of this Tuesday evening as I watch the SOTU address. What will be on your mind?

status_message:
Today's October 31st and that means everyone's focused on Halloween. But something else so very important happened today integral in the advancement of individual freedom and classical liberalism -- not this post-modern progressive Marxist/socialist crap. It was on this day, October 31st, in 1517 an Augustinian monk named Martin Luther nailed his 95 Theses to the door of the church in Wittenburg, Germany. Luther began what was to be known as the Protestant Reformation. He was declared a heretic, and Emperor Charles V ordered Luther apprehended and imprisoned, with possible death sentence, for not submitting to the Roman Catholic Church of Pope Leo X. Luther was protected and safeguarded by one Prince Frederick the Wise, Elector of Saxony. Luther died in 1546, and that year Charles V made an agreement with Pope Paul III to crush the Reformation.

In 1550, one German town refused to acquiesce, the city of Magdeburg. In October 1550, the pastors there wrote what came to be known as the Magdeburg Confession. That document's been translated from Latin and upon reading it, you'll see it provided a blueprint for the Declaration of Independence. Thank God for Martin Luther and the pastors of that one German city, Magdeburg, who held out against tyranny and taught the western world individuals can be free. And that, folks, is the ultimate treat to share with future generations!

status_message: I know Paul Ryan, but yesterday he said something very disturbing for me. He stated that he's willing to accept the position of being Speaker of the House as long as it doesn't interfere with his family time. Paul, let me advise you about the foolishness of that statement. Can you look into the eyes of any Soldier, Sailor, Airman, Marine, and Coast Guardsman and say that to them? Leadership is about service, sacrifice, and commitment. Those of us through the history of this great Constitutional Republic have had to sacrifice our family time for something greater: the commitment to freedom and liberty for our fellow Americans. The position of Speaker of the House is second in line after the President, the Commander-in-Chief. I just have to ask you a simple question: would you forego a Thanksgiving with your family to serve a Thanksgiving meal to our deployed Warriors? I humbly ask you to apologize to the men and women who have their family lives interrupted so politicians can make such inane statements.

status_message:
Last night, I had the distinct privilege of speaking at my alma mater, University of Tennessee, for the Young America's Foundation. The topic was our foreign policy and national security situation. I spoke to the audience of 200+ about how, when I arrived to Rocky Top in 1979, Iran held 52 American hostages; today, it holds four. I reminded them the Iranian Islamic revolution had begun; today, the Iranian regime is the number one state sponsor of Islamic terrorism. I recounted how, in 1979, the Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan; today, Russia's freely operating in Syria, occupying eastern Ukraine and taken the Crimea. I also shared with them how in the year of my graduation, 1983, Iranian-supported Hezbollah was responsible for the Beirut barracks bombing, killing 234 Marines, sailors and soldiers; today, their explosive force penetrators (EFPs) were responsible for some 30% of American deaths in Iraq. I reassured them we can rise above this, just as we did in 1980 with the election of Ronald Reagan and "peace through strength."

It was a great evening, and I even enjoyed the nutty professor with a long beard and overalls who introduced himself as some representative of an Islamic organization. He stated he wanted to debate me about my statement that "Islam is not consistent with the U.S. Constitution." Typical disturbed liberal Islamapologist — actually, that was Ben Carson who said that. But then again, I suppose all us black conservatives look alike -- what a chucklehead!

status_message: I got an email from a good friend, State Representative Doreen Costa of New Kingstown, Rhode Island. She wanted me to let you great Americans know about a little piece of aviation history she is trying to save. Now, y'all know I was a paratrooper so since I could not fly planes I jumped out of them. But hey, let's see what we can do to support the history of the fly boys. If you live in the area, fight to save the Quonset Air Museum. I've slept in Quonset huts in my military career in Korea. And we must honor the memory of the venerable US Navy Seabees. Part of the exceptionalism and greatness of America is preserving its past -- and Quonset Rhode Island deserves our efforts. Please contact Rep. Costa's office to find out how you can help. http://www.rilin.state.ri.us/representatives/Costa/Pages/Biography.aspx

status_message: Happy Constitution Day America.  228 years ago we created the rule of law for our Constitutional Republic embodied in this seminal document. James Madison prescribed the separation of powers, coequal branches of government, and the system of checks and balances which would ensure the federal government was constrained in its power. The Constitution clearly lays out our individual rights following Jefferson's declaration of our unalienable rights. Sadly, 228 years later we have a federal government that has turned its back on the Constitution and the system of federalism and our foundation as a Republic. It's as if we now more resemble a Constitutional Monarchy. Benjamin Franklin stated 228 years ago that "You have a Republic if you can keep it." Let us endeavor to live up to that challenge America. Happy Constitution Day from someone who took an oath to support and defend the Constitution against all enemies, foreign and domestic -- and I doggone will.

status_message: 9-11-2001, I had just finished morning PT and taken a shower at II Marine Expeditionary Force Hqs, Camp Lejeune North Carolina. I was in my office dressing when a call came from my counterpart at MARFORLANT (Marine Forces Atlantic) telling me to get to the Command Operations Center (COC) and look at the TV. By the time I got there, the second plane struck the World Trade Tower. We knew it was not by accident, since they were showing replay of the first plane hitting. Soon came the report on the Pentagon being struck, the Army G1, personnel, portion of the building. A dear friend of mine who is now a Texas State Senator, Brian Birdwell, was horribly burned. I will never forget that day, and how that evening the skies were silent. But sadly, there are those who have forgotten that day -- those who are funding and enabling the number one state sponsor of Islamic terrorism to bring more "Death to America." We must never forget 9-11 but more importantly, we must never forget the militant Islamic jihadist ideology that spurred forth this attack in 2001 and 2012.

What a blessing to stand next to American history. We must be committed to never forget and always honor the Greatest Generation and the sacrifices they made to defeat the evil of their time. status_message:
Ok, it is getting real close to my most favorite time of the year -- NCAA College Football season, and hat tip to the National Labor Relations Board for rejecting the Northwestern University suit filing for unionizing college football players. What is it about Chicago?

 Anyway, it's time to announce my college football travel plans for the regular season for my two favorite teams -- The University of Tennessee Volunteers and the Kansas State University Wildcats. Ok folks, I will be heading to Manhattan, Kansas on October 9th for the Saturday October 10th clash with the Texas Christian University Horned Frogs -- who are preseason ranked #2 in the nation. I am looking forward to this Big 12 battle of the Purple in the Little Apple -- EMAW!

And in the following month I will be headed to Rocky Top Tennessee with the family for the Tennessee homecoming and UT Army ROTC reunion -- we are ready to go back and fight ISIS -- November 14th against the University of North Texas.

I hope to visit with y'all and cheer on our team to victory! And I will also be heading over to Gerald J. Ford stadium to attend some SMU Mustangs football games with my daughter Aubrey who is studying for her Masters degree there. Oh yeah, this is my favorite time of the year.

status_message: Twenty years ago at this very moment I was a young US Army major stationed at Camp Casey Korea in the 2d Infantry Division. We got the news of a horrific bombing attack in Oklahoma City, 168 Americans lost their lives -- many children. It was a sad and terrible day. What made things even worse was to know that the person who executed this shameful, cowardly, and barbaric attack was a soldier with whom I had served in TF 2-16 Infantry of the 1st Infantry Division during Operation Desert Shield/Storm. He was a member of Charlie Company commanded by my dear friend, now retired Lieutenant Colonel, Scott Rutter. Years later I was able to walk the hallowed ground there in Oklahoma City, guest of Vickie and Scott Behenna -- parents of US Army Lieutenant Michael Behenna who was wrongfully incarcerated by the U.S. Army. Vickie was one of the federal prosecutors in the McVeigh case. I will never forget the news and seeing the images of that fateful day twenty years ago. The pain will never subside for those of whom those empty chairs represent. My humble condolences to those who lost their loved ones twenty years ago in Oklahoma City.

One hundred and fifty years ago today America's Civil War ended with the surrender of the Confederacy at Appomattox Court House in Virginia. However, 150 years later it seems America is embroiled in another civil war -- not as physically violent,t but nonetheless just as vicious. It is an ideological war pitting progressive socialism against constitutional conservatism. These two very different philosophies of governance advance two very different ideals- the former individual subservience and subjugation; the latter individual sovereignty and empowerment.

The bullets still fly -- 150 years ago the result was hundreds of thousands of lives lost. Today, the result is millions of Americans out of work and forced into government dependency. And anyone daring to stand against the progressive socialists face the bullets of character assassination -- a long, slow torture.

We are in a new civil war and just like the last, it is a struggle for the sanctity of the Union -- and it is hardly civil.

I must admit wholeheartedly, I am truly enjoying being here in Dallas. The welcome I have received has been just humbling. But I do have one very important announcement. Nevertheless, this past week on Tuesday I spoke to the Dallas Chapter of the Military Order of World Wars (I will be joining) at the Park City Club. Here is a picture for the ages. I am standing with US Army Lieutenant Colonel Charles Alford who fought in World War II in Patton's Third Army at the Battle of the Bulge and was part of the liberation of the infamous Buchenwald concentration camp. This ladies and gents is what America is all about, the legacy of service, sacrifice, and commitment which shall secure liberty and freedom while preserving our Republic by supporting and defending our Constitution against all enemies, foreign and domestic.

status_message: Congratulations to the University of Oregon Fighting Ducks and The Ohio State University Buckeyes for their triumphs yesterday in the first ever college football playoff. I must admit that this new system has been a resounding success in its first year. I almost expect it expanding to eight teams within the next five years. Well, there will be plenty of green and yellow along with scarlet and gray here in the Dallas metroplex in a few days. I think it will be a great game and we will see if the Buckeyes can slow down the infamous "Quack Attack". In the meantime would appreciate y'all joining me in cheering for my two alma maters today, Tennessee and Kansas State.
Forget Time Magazine and the AP, here are the top ten stories YOU thought were most important in 2014, based on most read. Some surprises...http://allenbwest.com/2015/01/top-10-stories-2014/
